daily_returns = df['Close'].pct_change().dropna()

daily_std = daily_returns.std()

annual_std = daily_std * np.sqrt(252)

threshold = 0
downside_returns = daily_returns[daily_returns < threshold]
downside_std = downside_returns.std() * np.sqrt(252)

print("Annualized Standard Deviation:", round(annual_std * 100, 2), "%")
print("Downside Risk:", round(downside_std * 100, 2), "%")

from prophet import Prophet
from prophet.plot import plot_plotly, plot_components_plotly

df = pd.read_csv('TSLA.csv')

df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])

one_year_ago = pd.Timestamp.today() - pd.DateOffset(years=1)
df = df[df['Date'] >= one_year_ago]

df = df[['Date', 'Close']]
df = df.rename(columns={'Date': 'ds', 'Close': 'y'})

model = Prophet(daily_seasonality=True)
model.fit(df)


future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=60)
forecast = model.predict(future)


fig = model.plot(forecast, xlabel='Date', ylabel='Close Price', figsize=(12, 8))
fig.set_facecolor('grey')

plt.title('Tesla Stock Prices with Trend Line, Future Prediction, and Seasonality')
plt.show()

fig2 = model.plot_components(forecast, figsize=(12, 8))
fig2.set_facecolor('grey')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


df = pd.read_csv('TSLA.csv', parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

close = df['Close']

sma20 = close.rolling(window=20).mean()
sma50 = close.rolling(window=50).mean()

buy_signals = (sma20 > sma50) & (sma20.shift() < sma50.shift())
sell_signals = (sma20 < sma50) & (sma20.shift() > sma50.shift())

plt.figure(figsize=(24,12))
plt.axes().set_facecolor('Black')
plt.scatter(close.index,close,marker=".", label='Closing Price', color="violet")
plt.plot(sma20, label='SMA (20)', color='blue')
plt.plot(sma50, label='SMA (50)', color='yellow')
plt.plot(sma20[buy_signals], '^', markersize=20, color='green', label='Buy Signal')
plt.plot(sma20[sell_signals], 'v', markersize=20, color='red', label='Sell Signal')
plt.legend()
plt.title('TSLA Stock Price (SMA Crossover Strategy)')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


df = pd.read_csv('TSLA.csv', parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

close = df['Close']

sma = close.rolling(window=20).mean()  
ema = close.ewm(span=50, adjust=False).mean()  

buy_signals = (ema < sma) & (ema.shift() > sma.shift())
sell_signals = (ema > sma) & (ema.shift() < sma.shift())

plt.figure(figsize=(24,12))
plt.axes().set_facecolor('Black')
plt.scatter(close.index, close, label='Closing Price',marker=".", color="violet")
plt.plot(sma, label='SMA (20)')
plt.plot(ema, label='EMA (50)', color='yellow')
plt.plot(ema[buy_signals], '^', markersize=20, color='green', label='Buy Signal')
plt.plot(ema[sell_signals], 'v', markersize=20, color='red', label='Sell Signal')
plt.legend()
plt.title('TSLA Stock Price (EMA Crossover Strategy)')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, LSTM, Dropout
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pd.read_csv('TSLA.csv', parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

data = df.filter(['Close']).values
train_len = int(len(data) * 0.8)

scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
scaled_data = scaler.fit_transform(data)

train_data = scaled_data[:train_len, :]
x_train = []
y_train = []
for i in range(60, train_len):
    x_train.append(train_data[i-60:i, 0])
    y_train.append(train_data[i, 0])
x_train, y_train = np.array(x_train), np.array(y_train)

x_train = np.reshape(x_train, (x_train.shape[0], x_train.shape[1], 1))

model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(units=50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(x_train.shape[1], 1)))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(LSTM(units=50, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(LSTM(units=50))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(units=1))

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error')

model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=32)

test_data = scaled_data[train_len - 60:, :]
x_test = []
y_test = data[train_len:, :]
for i in range(60, len(test_data)):
    x_test.append(test_data[i-60:i, 0])
x_test = np.array(x_test)
x_test = np.reshape(x_test, (x_test.shape[0], x_test.shape[1], 1))

predictions = model.predict(x_test)
predictions = scaler.inverse_transform(predictions)

import numpy as np

num_simulations = 100
num_days = 30
starting_price = df['Close'][-1]

returns = np.log(1 + df['Close'].pct_change()).dropna()
mu = returns.mean()
sigma = returns.std()

simulations = pd.DataFrame()
for i in range(num_simulations):
    prices = [starting_price]
    for j in range(num_days):
        price = prices[-1] * np.exp((mu - 0.5 * sigma**2) + sigma * np.random.normal())
        prices.append(price)
    simulations[i] = prices[0:]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4), facecolor='grey',edgecolor="green")
plt.axes().set_facecolor('black')
plt.plot(simulations)
plt.title('Monte Carlo Simulation for Tesla Stock Prices')
plt.xlabel('Day')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
